body:
# Prisma Database Seeding

Seed scripts populate your database with initial, development, or test data using [[prisma/client]].

## Setup

### Configuration (package.json)

```json
{
  "prisma": {
    "seed": "tsx prisma/seed.ts"
  }
}
```

Alternative runners:
- `"ts-node prisma/seed.ts"` — using ts-node
- `"node prisma/seed.js"` — plain JavaScript
- `"npx tsx prisma/seed.ts"` — using npx

### Install tsx (recommended TypeScript runner)

```bash
npm install tsx --save-dev
```

## Seed Script Template

```typescript
// prisma/seed.ts
import { PrismaClient } from '@prisma/client';

const prisma = new PrismaClient();

async function main() {
  // Use upsert for idempotent seeds (safe to run multiple times)
  const alice = await prisma.user.upsert({
    where: { email: 'alice@example.com' },
    update: {},
    create: {
      email: 'alice@example.com',
      name: 'Alice',
      role: 'ADMIN',
      posts: {
        create: [
          {
            title: 'Getting Started with Prisma',
            content: 'Prisma is a next-generation ORM...',
            published: true,
          },
          {
            title: 'Advanced Prisma Patterns',
            content: 'Let us explore transactions...',
            published: false,
          },
        ],
      },
    },
  });

  const bob = await prisma.user.upsert({
    where: { email: 'bob@example.com' },
    update: {},
    create: {
      email: 'bob@example.com',
      name: 'Bob',
      role: 'USER',
      profile: {
        create: { bio: 'Full-stack developer' },
      },
    },
  });

  // Seed lookup tables
  const tags = ['typescript', 'prisma', 'database', 'orm', 'nodejs'];
  for (const name of tags) {
    await prisma.tag.upsert({
      where: { name },
      update: {},
      create: { name },
    });
  }

  console.log('Seeded:', { alice: alice.email, bob: bob.email, tags: tags.length });
}

main()
  .then(async () => {
    await prisma.$disconnect();
  })
  .catch(async (e) => {
    console.error(e);
    await prisma.$disconnect();
    process.exit(1);
  });
```

## Running Seeds

```bash
# Run the seed script
npx prisma db seed

# Pass arguments to the seed script
npx prisma db seed -- --environment development

# Seeds also run after:
npx prisma migrate reset  # Drop + reapply migrations + seed
```

## Patterns

### Idempotent Seeds with upsert

Always use `upsert` instead of `create` so seeds can run multiple times without errors:

```typescript
await prisma.user.upsert({
  where: { email: 'alice@example.com' },
  update: {},  // Don't overwrite existing data
  create: { email: 'alice@example.com', name: 'Alice' },
});
```

### Environment-Specific Seeds

```typescript
const args = process.argv.slice(2);
const env = args.includes('--production') ? 'production' : 'development';

if (env === 'development') {
  // Seed test users, sample data
  await seedTestData();
}

// Always seed required lookup data
await seedLookupTables();
```

### Seeding with Faker

```typescript
import { faker } from '@faker-js/faker';

for (let i = 0; i < 50; i++) {
  await prisma.user.create({
    data: {
      email: faker.internet.email(),
      name: faker.person.fullName(),
      posts: {
        create: Array.from({ length: faker.number.int({ min: 0, max: 5 }) }, () => ({
          title: faker.lorem.sentence(),
          content: faker.lorem.paragraphs(3),
          published: faker.datatype.boolean(),
        })),
      },
    },
  });
}
```

### Batch Seeding with createMany

For large datasets, `createMany` is faster than individual `create` calls:

```typescript
await prisma.user.createMany({
  data: users,
  skipDuplicates: true,
});
```

Note: `createMany` doesn't support nested creates — use it for flat data.

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|--------|
| `DATABASE_URL` | Target database for seeding |
